docs.abstract: The Silicon Valley company was again lifted by sales of its artificial intelligence chips, but it faces growing competition and heightened expectations.
docs.snippet: The Silicon Valley company was again lifted by sales of its artificial intelligence chips, but it faces growing competition and heightened expectations.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nvidia, which makes microchips that power most artificial intelligence applications, began an extraordinary run a year ago.

headline.main: Nvidia, Powered by A.I. Boom, Reports Soaring Revenue and Profits
headline.print_headline: A.I. Boom Lifts Profits For Nvidia Even Higher

docs.abstract: The London-based developer of artificial intelligence systems for self-driving vehicles raised the funding from SoftBank, Nvidia, Microsoft and others.
docs.snippet: The London-based developer of artificial intelligence systems for self-driving vehicles raised the funding from SoftBank, Nvidia, Microsoft and others.
docs.lead_paragraph: Wayve, a London maker of artificial intelligence systems for autonomous vehicles, said on Tuesday that it had raised $1 billion, an eye-popping sum for a European start-up and an illustration of investor optimism about A.I.’s ability to reshape industries.

headline.main: Wayve, an A.I. Start-Up for Autonomous Driving, Raises $1 Billion
headline.print_headline: Wayve, an A.I. Start-Up for Autonomous Vehicles, Raises $1 Billion

docs.abstract: Expectations are sky-high for the chipmaker’s latest earnings report. The company is at the center of Wall Street’s focus on artificial intelligence.
docs.snippet: Expectations are sky-high for the chipmaker’s latest earnings report. The company is at the center of Wall Street’s focus on artificial intelligence.
docs.lead_paragraph: Despite concerns about stubbornly high inflation, elevated interest rates and ballooning U.S. debt, the S&P 500 is trading at a record on Wednesday, having soared 27 percent over the past year.

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni
